# Chapter-Specific Sub-Prompts for M.Tech Dissertation

Ab main har chapter ke liye dedicated sub-prompt bana raha hoon. Ye master prompt ke saath use honge, lekin har ek apne chapter ke specific writing style aur structure ko target karega.

Pehle main aapko ek important baat samjhata hoon. Har dissertation chapter ka apna character hota hai. Introduction emotional aur context-setting hoti hai. Literature review analytical hoti hai. Methodology procedural hoti hai. Results data-driven hoti hai. Conclusion reflective hoti hai. Agar ek hi style se sab likhenge toh dissertation flat lagega aur viva mein bhi guide pakad lega.

Toh chaliye ek ek karke dekhte hain.

---

## SUB-PROMPT 1: CHAPTER 1 — INTRODUCTION

```
You are writing CHAPTER 1: INTRODUCTION for an M.Tech dissertation.
All rules from the master prompt apply. Additional rules below are 
specific to this chapter.

================================================================
PURPOSE OF THIS CHAPTER
================================================================

The introduction sets the stage. It tells the reader what problem 
the project solves, why it matters in the Indian or global context, 
and what the dissertation will cover. It does not go deep into 
technical details. That comes later.

================================================================
EXPECTED STRUCTURE (FOLLOW IN ORDER)
================================================================

1.1 Background of the Work
    - Real-world context of the problem
    - Why this area is relevant today
    - Should feel grounded, not generic
    - Avoid lines like "In recent years, technology has advanced..."
    - Start with a specific observation or problem

1.2 Motivation
    - Personal or technical reason for choosing this topic
    - Can mention a real problem the student observed
    - Should sound genuine, not forced

1.3 Problem Statement
    - One clear paragraph stating exactly what problem is being solved
    - Should be specific, not vague
    - Avoid generic statements like "there is a need for better systems"

1.4 Objectives of the Work
    - List the main objectives (3 to 5 usually)
    - Each objective should be actionable and measurable
    - Use simple verbs like develop, design, analyze, implement, evaluate

1.5 Scope of the Work
    - What the project covers
    - What it does not cover (limitations of scope)

1.6 Organization of the Dissertation
    - Brief paragraph describing what each chapter contains
    - Keep it short, two to four lines per chapter
    - Avoid mechanical "Chapter 2 deals with... Chapter 3 deals with..." 
      pattern. Mix it up naturally.

================================================================
WRITING STYLE FOR THIS CHAPTER
================================================================

1. Tone is slightly narrative. The introduction tells a story of 
   why this work exists.
2. Avoid heavy technical jargon. Save that for later chapters.
3. Use first chapter to build context, not to prove expertise.
4. Mix short reflective sentences with longer descriptive ones.
5. Indian context can be added where relevant, like mentioning 
   challenges faced in Indian industries, healthcare, agriculture, 
   power sector, etc., if the project relates.

================================================================
COMMON MISTAKES TO AVOID
================================================================

1. Do not write a generic technology overview. The introduction 
   is about THIS project, not the field in general.
2. Do not repeat the abstract here.
3. Do not list every technical detail of the methodology.
4. Do not make the motivation section sound like a sales pitch.
5. Do not use "we" excessively. Use "the present work", "this 
   dissertation", "the proposed system".

================================================================

Now write Chapter 1 Introduction following all the rules above 
and the master prompt rules. Begin directly with the chapter content.
```

