## SUB-PROMPT 3: CHAPTER 3 — METHODOLOGY / PROPOSED WORK

```
You are writing CHAPTER 3: METHODOLOGY (or Proposed Work / System 
Design) for an M.Tech dissertation. All rules from the master prompt 
apply. Additional rules below are specific to this chapter.

================================================================
PURPOSE OF THIS CHAPTER
================================================================

This chapter explains exactly how the proposed work was designed and 
implemented. It is the technical heart of the dissertation. The 
reader should be able to understand the method clearly enough to 
imagine reproducing it.

================================================================
EXPECTED STRUCTURE (ADAPT TO PROJECT TYPE)
================================================================

3.1 Introduction to the Chapter
    - Brief overview of what the chapter explains

3.2 Proposed System Architecture or Block Diagram
    - High-level description of the system
    - Mention each block and its role
    - Reference a block diagram with [Insert Figure 3.1]

3.3 Detailed Description of Each Module or Stage
    - For each block, write a sub-section explaining its function
    - Cover inputs, outputs, internal processing
    - Use technical depth appropriate for M.Tech level

3.4 Algorithms or Mathematical Formulation
    - Present any equations using proper notation
    - Use [Insert Equation 3.1] style placeholders if needed
    - Explain what each variable represents
    - For algorithms, present them in a clean step-by-step manner

3.5 Tools, Hardware, or Software Used
    - List the tools with their versions if known
    - Briefly justify why each tool was chosen

3.6 Implementation Details
    - Specific configuration, parameter values, dataset details
    - Any preprocessing steps
    - Training parameters if ML based, simulation parameters if 
      circuit based, etc.

3.7 Summary
    - Short paragraph leading to the results chapter

================================================================
WRITING STYLE FOR THIS CHAPTER
================================================================

1. Tone is precise and technical, but still readable.
2. Use present tense when describing the system. "The system takes 
   the input image and applies preprocessing." Not past tense.
3. Be specific about parameters, sizes, dimensions, configurations.
4. Each module description should follow this rough flow: what it 
   does, how it does it, why this approach was chosen.
5. Avoid vague phrases like "appropriate techniques are used" or 
   "suitable parameters are selected". Always specify.

================================================================
TECHNICAL ACCURACY RULES (EXTRA STRICT HERE)
================================================================

1. Keep all technical names exactly as the user provided.
2. Do not invent algorithm names or technique names.
3. Do not change parameter values from what the user mentioned.
4. If a parameter value is not given, write [Specify parameter value] 
   instead of guessing.
5. Equations must be technically correct. If unsure about an 
   equation, write [Verify equation with guide] instead of 
   producing a wrong one.
6. Do not invent dataset names or sizes.

================================================================
DIAGRAMS AND FIGURES
================================================================

1. Reference figures naturally in text, like "as shown in Figure 3.1".
2. Use [Insert Figure 3.X: short description] as placeholder.
3. Do not try to draw ASCII diagrams.
4. Mention what the figure should contain so the student can create 
   it later.

================================================================
COMMON MISTAKES TO AVOID
================================================================

1. Do not write generic descriptions of standard algorithms. If you 
   describe CNN, do not write a textbook explanation of CNN. Describe 
   how CNN is used in this specific project.
2. Do not skip the justification of design choices.
3. Do not use bullet points for everything. Mix prose and structured 
   lists.
4. Do not copy standard architecture descriptions from papers.
5. Avoid making the chapter read like a manual. It should read like 
   a research design document.

================================================================

Now write Chapter 3 Methodology following all the rules above 
and the master prompt rules. Begin directly with the chapter content.
```

