## BONUS SUB-PROMPT: ABSTRACT

Yeh chhota hai lekin sabse important hai. Pehli cheez hai jo evaluator padhta hai.

```
You are writing the ABSTRACT for an M.Tech dissertation. All rules 
from the master prompt apply. Additional rules below are specific 
to the abstract.

================================================================
PURPOSE
================================================================

The abstract is a short standalone summary of the entire dissertation.
It is read by evaluators, external examiners, and anyone scanning 
the work. It must be self-contained.

================================================================
STRUCTURE (NO HEADINGS, ONE FLOWING TEXT)
================================================================

The abstract should cover, in this order, in flowing prose:

1. Context and problem (1 to 2 sentences)
2. The gap or motivation (1 sentence)
3. What was proposed in this work (2 to 3 sentences)
4. How it was implemented (1 to 2 sentences)
5. Key results achieved (1 to 2 sentences)
6. Conclusion or significance (1 sentence)

================================================================
LENGTH AND FORMAT
================================================================

1. Total length: 200 to 300 words. Strictly within this range.
2. Single paragraph. No headings. No bullet points.
3. No citations in the abstract.
4. No equations or figures referenced.
5. Add a "Keywords:" line at the bottom with 4 to 6 keywords 
   separated by commas.

================================================================
WRITING STYLE
================================================================

1. Use past tense for what was done. Present tense for what the 
   work demonstrates.
2. Be specific. Avoid vague phrases like "good results were obtained".
3. If the user has provided actual numerical results, include them 
   briefly. Otherwise, describe results qualitatively.
4. Tone is formal and dense. Every sentence carries weight.

================================================================
COMMON MISTAKES TO AVOID
================================================================

1. Do not write a generic introduction here.
2. Do not reference any chapter or figure.
3. Do not use phrases like "in this paper" or "this thesis presents". 
   Instead, use "the present work" or "this dissertation".
4. Do not promise things that the dissertation does not deliver.

================================================================

Now write the abstract following all rules above and the master 
prompt rules. Begin directly with the abstract content.
```

